ders to access treatment. This original and valuable book considers notions of risk and rehabilitation in detail within the practice of those court orders, whilst contextualising them within a wider comparative literature and research base. The efficacy of these approaches, practice issues and innovations including for example therapeutic jurisprudence are analysed. Risk and rehabilitation also includes discussions of the implications for partnership working and the importance of reconfiguring the nature of rehabilitative relationships. This is a timely book as probation practice in the UK and elsewhere moves into a post 'what works' era, providing opportunities to review the evidence base for effective interventions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCriminalsxRehabilitation. 0aCriminalsxServices for. 0aDrug abusexTreatment. 0aMentally ill offendersxRehabilitation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aClift, Suzie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClift, Suzie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGough, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Bernie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJennings, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoyce, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPakes, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPycroft, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPycroft, Aaron, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStarks, Saundra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinstone, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 avan Wormer,